'''Dobi Deene''' was a [[Jizz/Legends|jizz]] [[Musician/Legends|musician]] who wrote the song ''[[Wroonian Tramp]]''. Deene's [[Music/Legends|music]] was popular during the onset of the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]], when ''Wroonian tramp'' reached third in the charts.

==Biography==
Dobi Deene was a [[Jizz/Legends|jizz]]<ref name="ST">{{SW|url=news/slugthrowers-an-overview-of-popular-music-and-musicians-in-a-galaxy-far-far-away-part-1|series=Slugthrowers: An Overview of Popular Music and Musicians in a Galaxy Far, Far Away|text=Part 1|nolive=1}}</ref> [[Musician/Legends|musician]] whose [[Music/Legends|music]] was popular during the onset of the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]], a conflict between the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]] and the [[Confederacy of Independent Systems/Legends|Confederacy of Independent Systems]]. At one point in [[22 BBY/Legends|22 BBY]],<ref name="HNN">{{HoloNetNewsWeb|53||Top-Selling Sound Slugs}}</ref> the musician's unabashedly infectious song ''[[Wroonian Tramp]]'' topped out<ref name="ST" /> as the third best selling [[sound slug]]&mdash;a method of storing music&mdash;placing below only ''[[11011101 2]]'' by [[Plexo-33/Legends|Plexo-33]] and ''[[Stardance]]'' by [[Miracle Meriko]]. Deene's track did beat the songs ''[[Stark Memory]]'' by [[Lord Kavad and the Skaalite Orchestra]] and ''[[Does Anyone Weep?]]'' by [[Maxa Jandovar]] in terms of sales, which placed fourth and fifth respectively in the charts. Deene's chart position was reported in the [[HoloNet News Vol. 531 53|fifty-third]] issue of the [[HoloNet News Vol. 531|five hundred and thirty-first volume]] of the [[HoloNet News/Legends|HoloNet News]] [[HoloNet News CoCo District Edition|CoCo District Edition]].<ref name="HNN" />

==Behind the scenes==
Dobi Deene was first mentioned in [[2002]] on [[HoloNet News (original website)|''Holonet News'']], a website written from an in-universe perspective which was published as part of the build-up to the film [[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones|''Star Wars'': Episode II ''Attack of the Clones'']]. Deene's name was included on a top selling music chart, which was part of the homepage of the website in [[HoloNet News Vol. 531 53]]. Deene was mentioned again in ''[[Slugthrowers: An Overview of Popular Music and Musicians in a Galaxy Far, Far Away]]'', an article written by [[Edward M. Erdelac]] and released on the [[StarWars.com]] [[Star Wars Blog|blog]] in [[2013]].

